>cave</i> ‘cave’, ‘cellar’ (from Latin <i>cavea</i>, a derivative of <i>cavus</i> ‘hollow’)."],"variants":[{"name":"Cavin","meanings":["Scottish (Wigtownshire): variant of <b>Caveen</b>, a shortened form of Manx <i>Mac Dhaimhín</i>, son of <i>Daimhín</i>. The personal name is a diminutive of Gaelic <i>damh</i> ‘bard, poet’.","French: diminutive of   Cave  ."]},{"name":"Caves","meanings":["English: variant of   Cave  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Keeve","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of   Cave  . This surname is rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Chaffee","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): descriptive nickname from a derivative of Old French <i>chauf</i> ‘bald’ (from Latin <i>calvus</i>). Compare   Cave  ."]},{"name":"Cavett","meanings":["Scottish (of French origin): altered form of French <b>Cavet</b>, which is either a diminutive of   Cave   3 or a metonymic occupational name for a laborer, one who used a <i>cavet</i>, an Old Occitan word for a tool for clearing ground for cultivation."]}]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Alexander Cave was born in 1335, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. He married Catherine de Grindell about 1359, in Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of a